<subSubSection id="11C46515FFFAFFEFFF02364733FB94E8" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="5961369EFFFAFFEFFF02364733FB94E8" blockId="1.[151,1436,1369,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFFAFFEFFF02364736659461" bold="true" box="[199,309,1369,1393]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Both males and females of 
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFFAFFEFFDAC364434D19461" box="[617,897,1370,1393]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
Melichyopharis 
<taxonomicName id="9EDE4D1DFFFAFFEFFCDD364434D19461" box="[792,897,1370,1393]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Melychiopharis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bibendum">bibendum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
differ from 
<taxonomicName id="9EDE4D1DFFFAFFEFFBC33644333A9461" box="[1030,1130,1370,1393]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Melychiopharis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cinips">
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFFAFFEFFBC33644333A9461" box="[1030,1130,1370,1393]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">M. cinips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="3D4F4B6FFFFAFFEFFB61364732399460" author="Santos" box="[1188,1385,1369,1393]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" refString="Santos, A. J., Brescovit, A. D. &amp; Levi, H. W. (2005) Melychiopharis: an atypical orb-weaving spider from South America (Araneae: Araneidae). Zootaxa, 1016, 57 - 64." type="journal article" year="2005">
Santos 
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFFAFFEFFB37364432799461" box="[1266,1321,1370,1393]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFAF5364732399460" box="[1328,1385,1369,1392]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFF523665379D9482" box="[151,205,1403,1426]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="8.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="6.0">6–10</number>
) in the stronger granulation of carapace (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFD643665345E9482" box="[673,782,1403,1426]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Figs. 1, 2</figureCitation>
) and in the remarkable tubercles at the anterior margin of abdomen, around the pedicel (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFE1C3683354B94A4" box="[473,539,1437,1460]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
Fig. 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFDCE3683354B94A4" box="[523,539,1437,1460]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). Males also differ in the longer embolus with a small rounded basis (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFAC73683321D94A4" box="[1282,1357,1437,1460]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFA9C3683323794A4" box="[1369,1383,1437,1460]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1311,1334]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,592,1279]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,583,1290]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 7, Male pedipalp, prolateral view; 8, ditto, retrolateral view; 9, female epigynum, ventral view; 10, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; E, embolus; FD, fertilization ducts; M, median plate of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium; SP, spermathecae. Scale bars: 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277032/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">7</figureCitation>
) and the larger paracymbium (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFE6036A136B694C6" box="[421,486,1471,1494]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFE3736A1355194C6" box="[498,513,1471,1494]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1311,1334]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,592,1279]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,583,1290]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 7, Male pedipalp, prolateral view; 8, ditto, retrolateral view; 9, female epigynum, ventral view; 10, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; E, embolus; FD, fertilization ducts; M, median plate of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium; SP, spermathecae. Scale bars: 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277032/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">8</figureCitation>
). Females can be distinguished by the median plate of epigynum subtriangular, with a narrow anterior septum (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFE5B36FF36B994E8" box="[414,489,1505,1528]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Figs. 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFE3036FF355394E8" box="[501,515,1505,1528]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1311,1334]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,592,1279]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,583,1290]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 7, Male pedipalp, prolateral view; 8, ditto, retrolateral view; 9, female epigynum, ventral view; 10, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; E, embolus; FD, fertilization ducts; M, median plate of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium; SP, spermathecae. Scale bars: 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277032/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">9</figureCitation>
) and the copulatory ducts wider and not encapsulated (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFB8A36FF33CF94E8" box="[1103,1183,1505,1528]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1311,1334]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,592,1279]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,583,1290]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 7, Male pedipalp, prolateral view; 8, ditto, retrolateral view; 9, female epigynum, ventral view; 10, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; E, embolus; FD, fertilization ducts; M, median plate of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium; SP, spermathecae. Scale bars: 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277032/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
Fig. 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFB4436FF33CF94E8" box="[1153,1183,1505,1528]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="11C46515FFFAFFECFF02351C36C391E2" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="63" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" type="description">
<paragraph id="5961369EFFFAFFEFFF02351C345C967C" blockId="1.[151,1436,1369,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFFAFFEFFF02351C361B970A" bold="true" box="[199,331,1538,1562]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Description</emphasis>
. Male. Carapace longer than wide, widest at the middle. Carapace, sternum and legs red-brown. Lateral and part of dorsum of opisthosoma yellow, with a large central, brown spot and two posterior marginal black patches (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFF5A3558378F974D" box="[159,223,1606,1629]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
Fig. 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFF173558378F974D" box="[210,223,1606,1629]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Venter reddish anteriorly and orange posteriorly. Eyes subequal in size. Anterior median eyes separated by its diameters, almost one diameter from posterior medians. Lateral eyes approximately half a diameter from the anterior medians. Median ocular quadrangle almost square. Clypeus 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFCE63594341497B1" box="[803,836,1674,1697]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.5">1.5</number>
anterior median eyes diameter high. Opisthosoma 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFAA8359432CC97B1" box="[1389,1436,1674,1697]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.1">1.10</number>
long, 1.0 wide, covered with a single, dish-shaped dorsal scutum, with a lateral flange (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFB8E35B233DB97D3" box="[1099,1163,1708,1731]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
Fig. 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFBBB35B233DB97D3" box="[1150,1163,1708,1731]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Venter with an anterior and a posterior sclerotized area to the epigastric groove. Anterior sclerotized area with a marked posterior sulcus. Colulus small, without setae. Total length 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFDCE35EE357F9617" box="[523,559,1776,1799]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="2.1">2.1</number>
. Carapace 1.0 long, 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFCD435EE34629617" box="[785,818,1776,1799]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="0.6">0.6</number>
wide. Femur I 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFC1A35EE33539617" box="[991,1027,1776,1799]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="2.2">2.2</number>
, patella and tibia 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFB0D35EE33BB9617" box="[1224,1259,1776,1799]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.8">1.8</number>
, metatarsus 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFAB135EE32C79617" box="[1396,1431,1776,1799]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.2">1.2</number>
, tarsus 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFF1E340C36509639" box="[219,256,1810,1833]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="0.7">0.7</number>
. Patella and tibia II 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFE11340C36A79639" box="[468,503,1810,1833]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.7">1.7</number>
, III 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFDE1340C35179639" box="[548,583,1810,1833]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.3">1.3</number>
, IV 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFDB0340C35C99639" box="[629,665,1810,1833]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.8">1.8</number>
. Legs without femoral spines. Macrosetae absent on male palpal patella. Tegulum elongated mesally, with a rounded, sclerotized hump. Median apophysis distally bent (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFB4A342D338A965A" box="[1167,1242,1843,1866]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFB20342D33A5965A" box="[1253,1269,1843,1866]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1311,1334]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,592,1279]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,583,1290]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 7, Male pedipalp, prolateral view; 8, ditto, retrolateral view; 9, female epigynum, ventral view; 10, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; E, embolus; FD, fertilization ducts; M, median plate of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium; SP, spermathecae. Scale bars: 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277032/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">7</figureCitation>
). Paracymbium curved, convex, and rectangular in dorsal view (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFD5D344B35B3967C" box="[664,739,1877,1900]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFD2A344B35AE967C" box="[751,766,1877,1900]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1311,1334]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,592,1279]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,583,1290]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 7, Male pedipalp, prolateral view; 8, ditto, retrolateral view; 9, female epigynum, ventral view; 10, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; E, embolus; FD, fertilization ducts; M, median plate of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium; SP, spermathecae. Scale bars: 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277032/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5961369EFFFAFFECFF02346936C391E2" blockId="1.[151,1436,1369,2036]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,152,548]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="63" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
Female. Body shape and coloration as in male (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFFAFFEFFD173469340A969E" box="[722,858,1911,1934]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
Figs. 2, 5, 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFC8F3469340A969E" box="[842,858,1911,1934]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). Relative eye interdistances as in male. Clypeus 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFABE346932CC969E" box="[1403,1436,1911,1934]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="2.5">2.5</number>
anterior median eyes diameter high. Total length 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFD723487358B96A0" box="[695,731,1945,1968]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="2.2">2.2</number>
, carapace 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFC8B3487343F96A0" box="[846,879,1945,1968]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="0.9">0.9</number>
long, 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFC7C3487348B96A0" box="[953,987,1945,1968]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="0.6">0.6</number>
wide. Femur I 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFB4C348733FD96A0" box="[1161,1197,1945,1968]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="0.8">0.8</number>
, patella and tibia 2.0, metatarsus 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFED734A5366696C2" box="[274,310,1979,2002]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.4">1.4</number>
, tarsus 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFE4F34A536FF96C2" box="[394,431,1979,2002]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="0.7">0.7</number>
. Patella and tibia II 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFD4A34A535E396C2" box="[655,691,1979,2002]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.9">1.9</number>
, III 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFD2134A5345896C2" box="[740,776,1979,2002]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.4">1.4</number>
, IV 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFCFF34A5340E96C2" box="[826,862,1979,2002]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.7">1.7</number>
. Legs without femoral spines. Macrosetae absent on female palpal patella. Opisthosoma 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFDDB34C3356F96E4" box="[542,575,2013,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.2">1.2</number>
long, 
<number id="EF1624B9FFFAFFEFFD4234C335F996E4" box="[647,681,2013,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" value="1.1">1.1</number>
wide, similar to the male, except by the shorter posterior sclerotized area (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFF9FFECFF163386364591BF" box="[211,277,152,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1242,1265]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,187,1226]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,181,1230]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 1, Male habitus, dorsal view; 2, female habitus, dorsal view; 3, male pedipalp, prolateral view; 4, ditto, retrolateral view; 5, female abdomen, ventral view; 7, ditto, antero-ventral view (arrow points to anterior tubercles). Abbreviations: C, conductor; E, embolus; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277031/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
Fig. 
<number id="EF1624B9FFF9FFECFEC33386364591BF" box="[262,277,152,175]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). Copulatory openings located on the side of the median plate of epigynum. Copulatory ducts long, twisted and enlarged on the base of spermathecae. Spermathecae rounded and close together. Fertilization ducts long, basal to the spermathecae (
<figureCitation id="C1E52A1BFFF9FFECFEF333C536D691E2" box="[310,390,219,242]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1311,1334]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,592,1279]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,583,1290]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 10. Melychiopharis bibendum n. sp. 7, Male pedipalp, prolateral view; 8, ditto, retrolateral view; 9, female epigynum, ventral view; 10, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Abbreviations: C, conductor; CD, copulatory ducts; E, embolus; FD, fertilization ducts; M, median plate of epigynum; MA, median apophysis; PC, paracymbium; SP, spermathecae. Scale bars: 4.7 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/277032/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
Fig. 
<number id="EF1624B9FFF9FFECFEAD33C536D691E2" box="[360,390,219,242]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="11C46515FFF9FFECFF0233E333F490CF" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5961369EFFF9FFECFF0233E336D0906A" blockId="2.[151,1436,152,548]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFF9FFECFF0233E336659005" bold="true" box="[199,309,253,277]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Remarks.</emphasis>
The long and granulated carapace of the 
<typeStatus id="8665883CFFF9FFECFD2933E3344A9004" box="[748,794,253,276]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">type</typeStatus>
specimens, together with the genitalic characters mentioned in the genus diagnosis supports the placement of this species in 
<taxonomicName id="9EDE4D1DFFF9FFECFC633201331D9026" box="[934,1101,287,310]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Melychiopharis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFF9FFECFC633201331D9026" box="[934,1101,287,310]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Melychiopharis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="9EDE4D1DFFF9FFECFBA13201325B9026" box="[1124,1291,287,310]" class="Arachnida" family="Araneidae" genus="Melychiopharis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFF9FFECFBA13201325B9026" box="[1124,1291,287,310]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Melychiopharis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably monophyletic, supported by at least the modified carapace and the filiform median apophysis (see additional comments in 
<bibRefCitation id="3D4F4B6FFFF9FFECFF77327D3625906A" author="Santos" box="[178,373,355,378]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" refString="Santos, A. J., Brescovit, A. D. &amp; Levi, H. W. (2005) Melychiopharis: an atypical orb-weaving spider from South America (Araneae: Araneidae). Zootaxa, 1016, 57 - 64." type="journal article" year="2005">
Santos et al. 
<number id="EF1624B9FFF9FFECFEFE327D3625906A" box="[315,373,355,378]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5961369EFFF9FFECFF02329A33F490CF" blockId="2.[151,1436,152,548]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFF9FFECFF02329A3626908C" bold="true" box="[199,374,388,412]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Natural history</emphasis>
. The specimens were collected by nocturnal visual search on 
<collectingCountry id="21C9760EFFF9FFECFBD9329A3303908B" box="[1052,1107,388,411]" name="Malta" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Mata</collectingCountry>
Atlântica area of the 
<collectingCountry id="21C9760EFFF9FFECFA87329A3229908B" box="[1346,1401,388,411]" name="Malta" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Mata</collectingCountry>
do Pacangê, in the south of Bahia, but unfortunately the web was not observed by the collectors. The specimens were found at low abundance (only two individuals) in a study where 
<number id="EF1624B9FFF9FFECFCC732D6346E90CF" box="[770,830,456,479]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" value="2406.0">2,406</number>
spider specimens were collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="11C46515FFF9FFECFF0232F433CD9311" box="[199,1181,490,514]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5961369EFFF9FFECFF0232F433CD9311" blockId="2.[151,1436,152,548]" box="[199,1181,490,514]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis id="6BAAEA8CFFF9FFECFF0232F436029312" bold="true" box="[199,338,490,514]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Distribution</emphasis>
. Know only from the 
<typeStatus id="8665883CFFF9FFECFDFA32F4353D9311" box="[575,621,490,513]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">type</typeStatus>
locality in the state of Bahia, northeastern of 
<collectingCountry id="21C9760EFFF9FFECFB9132F433C99311" box="[1108,1177,490,513]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
